# Convex Validator Patterns

## Document Validator Utilities

Use the `doc` and `docs` utilities from `convex/lib/validators.ts` for consistent return validators that automatically include Convex system fields (`_id`, `_creationTime`):

```ts
import { doc, docs } from '../../lib/validators';

// Single document (default: non-nullable)
export const getItemReturns = doc('items'); // Guaranteed to exist

// Single document (nullable)
export const getItemReturns = doc('items', true); 

// Array of documents
export const listItemsReturns = docs('items');
```

**Benefits:**
- Automatic system field inclusion
- Consistent nullable/non-nullable patterns  
- Type-safe with schema changes
- Reduces boilerplate validator definitions

## Reusable Validators

Per [Convex Stack: Keep validators from going stale](https://stack.convex.dev/types-cookbook#keep-validators-from-going-stale), export field objects from `schema.ts` to maintain consistency:

### Export Field Objects

```ts
// convex/schema.ts
export const statusType = v.union(
  v.literal('approved'),
  v.literal('archived'),
  v.literal('backlog'),
  v.literal('published'),
);

export const timestampFields = {
  // Convex provides a `_creationTime` field automatically
  deletedAt: v.optional(v.number()),
  updatedAt: v.optional(v.number()),
};

// Export field objects (without system fields)
export const itemFields = {
  ...timestampFields,
  description: v.optional(v.string()),
  status: statusType,
  title: v.string(),
};

// Use in schema
export default defineSchema({
  items: defineTable(itemFields).index('by_status', ['status']),
});
```

### Use `doc` and `docs` for Return Validators

Use the `doc` and `docs` utilities from `convex/lib/validators.ts` for consistent return validators that include system fields:

```ts
// convex/model/items/validators.ts
import { doc, docs } from '../../lib/validators';

// Single document (can be null)
export const getItemReturns = doc('items', true); 

// Single document (guaranteed to exist in context)
export const getItemWithRelationsReturns = v.union(
  v.object({
    item: doc('items'), // Guaranteed to exist (default: false)
    author: doc('users', true), 
    tags: docs('tags'), // Array of documents
  }),
  v.null(),
);

// Array of documents
export const listItemsReturns = docs('items');
```

**When to use `nullable: true`:**
- Direct lookups that might not find the document
- Optional relationships in composite returns

**When to use default `nullable: false`:**
- Documents guaranteed to exist in the current context
- Main entity in composite returns where you've already checked existence

### Mutation Args: Use Subsets

For mutations, define args separately (often a subset of fields):

```ts
export const create = mutation({
  args: {
    // Only user-provided fields (no auto-generated timestamps/slugs)
    description: v.optional(v.string()),
    status: v.optional(statusType), // ✅ Reuse common validators
    title: v.string(),
  },
  // ...
});
```

### Composite Return Types

For queries that join multiple tables, use `doc` and `docs` utilities for consistent system field handling:

```ts
// ✅ Best - Use doc/docs utilities
returns: v.union(
  v.object({
    item: doc('items'), // Guaranteed to exist (default: false)
    owner: doc('users', true), 
    tags: docs('tags'), // Array of documents
  }),
  v.null(),
)

// ⚠️ Only if structure is too complex
returns: v.union(
  v.object({
    item: v.any(), // Doc<"items">
    owner: v.union(v.any(), v.null()), // Doc<"users"> | null
  }),
  v.null(),
)
```

**Why:** The `doc` and `docs` utilities automatically include Convex system fields (`_id`, `_creationTime`) and stay in sync with schema changes.

## Type Safety

### Avoid `v.any()`

Use specific validators instead of `v.any()` to maintain type safety:

```ts
import { doc } from '../lib/validators';

// ❌ Bad - loses all type safety
export const getUser = query({
  args: { id: v.id('users') },
  returns: v.any(),
  handler: async (ctx, { id }) => {
    return await ctx.db.get(id);
  },
});

// ✅ Good - uses doc utility for type safety and system fields
export const getUser = query({
  args: { id: v.id('users') },
  returns: doc('users', true), 
  handler: async (ctx, { id }) => {
    return await ctx.db.get(id);
  },
});
```

**When `v.any()` is acceptable:**
- Complex joined types where exact structure can't be defined
- Pagination return types (see below)
- Always add TypeScript comment to document expected type
- Use `v.object()` with specific fields when possible

```ts
// ✅ Acceptable with comment
returns: v.object({
  post: v.any(), // Doc<"posts">
  author: v.union(v.any(), v.null()), // Doc<"users"> | null
})
```

## Pagination Return Types

Convex pagination uses `v.any()` as the standard pattern per official documentation. Convex does not provide a built-in pagination result validator.

Always document pagination returns with a JSDoc comment:

```ts
/**
 * Pagination return type uses v.any() per Convex standard pattern.
 * See: https://docs.convex.dev/database/pagination
 *
 * Returns: PaginationResult<Doc<'tableName'>>
 * Structure: { page: Doc<'tableName'>[], continueCursor: string, isDone: boolean }
 */
export const listItemsReturns = v.any();
```

**For enriched pagination results:**

```ts
/**
 * Pagination return type uses v.any() per Convex standard pattern.
 * See: https://docs.convex.dev/database/pagination
 *
 * Returns: PaginationResult with enriched page
 * Structure: { page: Array<Doc<'items'> & { owner: Doc<'users'> | null }>, continueCursor: string, isDone: boolean }
 */
export const listItemsWithOwnersReturns = v.any();
```

**Why this is the standard pattern:**
- Convex doesn't provide a `v.paginationResult()` validator
- The `page` array can be transformed (mapped/filtered), making static typing impractical
- Official docs show no examples of typing pagination returns
- Reference: https://docs.convex.dev/database/pagination

## Index Optimization

### Redundant Indexes

Compound indexes can be used for prefix queries - remove redundant single-field indexes:

```ts
// ✅ Optimal
.index('by_user_and_category', ['userId', 'categoryId'])

// ❌ Redundant (already covered by compound index above)
.index('by_user', ['userId'])
```

Use compound index for both queries:
```ts
// Query by prefix only
.withIndex('by_user_and_category', (q) => q.eq('userId', id))

// Query by full compound
.withIndex('by_user_and_category', (q) => q.eq('userId', id).eq('categoryId', catId))
```

**Exception:** Keep both only if you need different sort orders.

### Schema Audit Checklist

1. Remove indexes that are prefixes of compound indexes
2. Remove unused indexes
3. Add indexes for filtered fields with large result sets (1000+)
4. Use pagination/`.take()` instead of `.collect()` for large queries
5. Replace `v.any()` with specific validators where possible
6. Add TypeScript comments for any remaining `v.any()` usage
